{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-003", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 4, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 1, "target_segment_count": 1, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.4", "chinese_text": "神得一以靈，", "translation_ref": "老子 39.3", "translation_text": "Earth rendered thereby firm and sure;"}
{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-004", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 5, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 2, "target_segment_count": 3, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.5 - 老子 39.6", "chinese_text": "谷得一以盈，萬物得一以生，", "translation_ref": "老子 39.4 - 老子 39.6", "translation_text": "Spirits with powers by it supplied; Valleys kept full throughout their void All creatures which through it do live"}
{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-005", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 7, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 1, "target_segment_count": 2, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.7", "chinese_text": "侯王得一以為天下貞。", "translation_ref": "老子 39.7 - 老子 39.8", "translation_text": "Princes and kings who from it get The model which to all they give."}
{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-006", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 8, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 2, "target_segment_count": 2, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.8 - 老子 39.9", "chinese_text": "其致之，天無以清將恐裂，", "translation_ref": "老子 39.9 - 老子 39.10", "translation_text": "All these are the results of the One (Dao). If heaven were not thus pure, it soon would rend;"}
{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-007", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 10, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 1, "target_segment_count": 1, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.10", "chinese_text": "地無以寧將恐發，", "translation_ref": "老子 39.11", "translation_text": "If earth were not thus sure, 'twould break and bend;"}
{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-008", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 11, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 2, "target_segment_count": 3, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.11 - 老子 39.12", "chinese_text": "神無以靈將恐歇，谷無以盈將恐竭，", "translation_ref": "老子 39.12 - 老子 39.14", "translation_text": "Without these powers, the spirits soon would fail; If not so filled, the drought would parch each vale; Without that life, creatures would pass away;"}
{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-009", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 13, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 1, "target_segment_count": 2, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.13", "chinese_text": "萬物無以生將恐滅，", "translation_ref": "老子 39.15 - 老子 39.16", "translation_text": "Princes and kings, without that moral sway, However grand and high, would all decay."}
{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-010", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 14, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 2, "target_segment_count": 1, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.14 - 老子 39.15", "chinese_text": "侯王無以貴高將恐蹶。故貴以賤為本，", "translation_ref": "老子 39.17", "translation_text": "Thus it is that dignity finds its (firm) root in its (previous) meanness, and what is lofty finds its stability in the lowness (from which it rises)."}
{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-011", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 16, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 3, "target_segment_count": 1, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.16 - 老子 39.18", "chinese_text": "高以下為基。是以侯王自稱孤﹑寡﹑不穀。此非以賤為本邪？", "translation_ref": "老子 39.18", "translation_text": "Hence princes and kings call themselves 'Orphans,' 'Men of small virtue,' and as 'Carriages without a nave.' Is not this an acknowledgment that in their considering themselves mean they see the foundation of their dignity?"}
{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-012", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 19, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 2, "target_segment_count": 1, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.19 - 老子 39.20", "chinese_text": "非乎？故致數輿無輿，", "translation_ref": "老子 39.19", "translation_text": "So it is that in the enumeration of the different parts of a carriage we do not come on what makes it answer the ends of a carriage."}
{"alignment_id": "laozi-chapter-039__align-013", "work_id": "laozi", "section_id": "laozi-chapter-039", "alignment_type": "exact_or_near_exact", "confidence": 1.0, "order": 21, "section_unit": "chapter", "segment_type": "sentence", "alignment_granularity": "grouped", "is_coarse_alignment": false, "coarse_alignment_reason": null, "source_segment_count": 2, "target_segment_count": 1, "chinese_ref": "老子 39.21 - 老子 39.22", "chinese_text": "不欲琭琭如玉，珞珞如石。", "translation_ref": "老子 39.20", "translation_text": "They do not wish to show themselves elegant-looking as jade, but (prefer) to be coarse-looking as an (ordinary) stone."}
